Such an embarrassment of riches was inconceivable to the man who discovered <ENAMEX TYPE="LOC">the Burgess Shale</ENAMEX> , one <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Charles Doolittle Walcott</ENAMEX> .
The received <ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Darwinian</ENAMEX> wisdom of <ENAMEX TYPE="DATE">the day</ENAMEX> said that animals living so long ago must be simple in design , limited in scope and ancestral to contemporary species .
Accordingly , the hidebound traditionalist reconstructed hypothetical organisms from the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOC">Burgess</ENAMEX> fossils in such a way that they could be shoehorned into familiar categories .
It was not until <ENAMEX TYPE="DATE">the early 1970s</ENAMEX> that <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Cambridge</ENAMEX> Prof. <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Harry Whittington</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">two</ENAMEX> sharp graduate students began to publish a reinterpretation of <ENAMEX TYPE="LOC">the Burgess Shale</ENAMEX> .
